node.text:
Not sure if you all on IG will wanna watch me demo software, but we just added the ability to Give Flowers (Give Thanks) within Cerebro. I wanted a way for anyone at @776fund to be able to record when someone does something kind for them. Why? Because it's really important to know who your allies are + find ways to do right by em. 💐💐💐

Imagine the social graph we will have in a decade when we know all the kindness that's been extended / received in our network. Take it from the guy who coined "Karma" on Reddit -- this is going to be very valuable for ‪7️⃣7️⃣6️⃣‬ and our founders. ‪#BuildInPublic‬

Yes, Venture Capitalists can believe in Karma.

node.text: My birthday is today, April 24, which is also Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day... One of my earliest childhood memories was being told on this day (maybe my 5th birthday?) that I had a tremendous responsibility to make the most out of the opportunity my family had sacrificed so much for. 🇦🇲🙏 That's why recognition is such a small act that means so much to us, especially Armenian-Americans who've watched every single President bow to Turkey and their propaganda of denial. No more.

@michaelsidgmore and I did our first ever #comXcap in person and I didn't properly focus the camera 😖 but we had a great chat about the new intersection of Work & Play.

We talked about gaming platforms @sorare_official and @axieinfinity ➡️ the gamification of work. We’ve entered the next stage of the gamification of the internet. It’s now become the gamification of work.

With games like Axie, a Pokemon-like game built on the Ethereum blockchain where people breed, battle, and trade digital pets called Axies, users may be playing a game, but they might also be earning a living.

There are countless people making more money breeding Axies than they are in their current jobs. Heck, many people in the Philippines and Vietnam have quit their jobs because they make a better living playing Axie. And tens of thousands of new players are joining the game each day, in large part because of the community and the Axie economy.

We talk about the implications of people playing a game to earn a living. And those implications are profound.

What does it means for the future of work? What does it mean for education? How do we prepare for a future where people can own their life - in a physical or virtual world?

So, now, what’s the distinction between work and play? Listen the episode wherever you get your pods 🎧 Community x Capital
